es:  Indian Dilip, Anirban, Gopal, Alok, Anindya, Arunava, Asit, Asok, Dibyendu, Goutam, Indra, Indranil.","Indian: variant of   Dey  ."],"variants":[{"name":"Dey","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Indian Ashit, Indu, Naina, Partha, Soumya, Ajit, Anjan, Anjana, Anup, Arjun, Arun, Ashim.","English, Scottish, and Welsh: variant of   Day  .","German: topographic name from a field name in North Rhine-Westphalia, denoting a sizeable piece of land, from Middle Low German <i>dē</i> ‘thigh’ (referring to the shape of the property)."]}]},{"name":"MARMION","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Irish: perhaps an Anglicized form of an unidentified Gaelic name. Compare   Merriman  .","English (Lancashire; of Norman origin) and French: nickname from Old French <i>marmion</i> ‘monkey, brat’."],"variants":[{"name":"Merriman","meanings":["English:","nickname from Middle English <i>mirie</i>, <i>merie</i>, <i>murie</i> ‘merry, pleasant’ + <i>man</i> ‘man’. Compare   Merry   1. This surname is established in Ireland (perhaps as an Anglicized form of an unidentified Gaelic name; compare   Marmion  ) as well as England.","there has probably been some confusion with <b>Marriman</b>, probably an occupational name meaning ‘servant of <i>Mary</i>’, from the female personal name <i>Mary</i> (see   Marie  ) + Middle English <i>man</i> in the sense ‘servant’, or perhaps a pet form of <i>Mary</i> using the hypocoristic suffix -<i>man</i>. The surname <i>Marriman</i> is now vanishingly rare in Britain and Ireland."]},{"name":"Marmon","meanings":["English (Lancashire and Gloucestershire):","variant of   Marmion  .","variant of <b>Marriman</b>, an occupational name meaning ‘servant of Mary’, from the female personal name <i>Mary</i> (see   Marie  ) + Middle English <i>man</i> in the sense ‘servant’."]}]},{"name":"ALICE","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Originally a variant of   Adelaide  , representing an Old French spelling of a reduced form of Germanic <i>Adalheidis</i>. <i>Alice</i> and <i>Adelaide</i> were already regarded as distinct names in English during the medieval period. <i>Alice</i> enjoyed a surge of popularity in the 19th century and periods of favour ever since. It was the name of the central character of  Lewis Carroll's  Alice's Adventures in Wonderland (  1865 ) and Through the Looking Glass (  1872 ), who was based on his child friend  Alice Liddell , daughter of the Dean of Christ Church, Oxford."],"variants":[{"name":"Alys","meanings":["Variant spelling of   Alice ."]},{"name":"Alis","meanings":["equivalent of <b>Alice</b> ."]}]}],"lifeSummary":"When ALICE DE MARMION was born in 1303, in Warwickshire, England, United Kingdom, her father, Sir Robert de Marmion, was 40 and her mother, Isabella Fitz Ralph, was 30. She married JOHN DE WHITACRE in 1345, in England, United Kingdom. They were the parents of at least 1 daughter. She died in December 1350, in her hometown, at the age of 47."},"et":{"1303–DEC 1350":"1303–detsember 1350","1278–1334":"1278–1334","1300–Female":"1300–Surnud","1303–1350":"1303–1350","1315–Female":"1315–Surnud","1300–1349":"1300–1349","1293–Male":"1293–Surnud","1349–1412":"1349–1412","1263–1316":"1263–1316","1273–Female":"1273–Surnud","1263":"1263","1273":"1273","1350":"1350","1293":"1293","Abt 1349":"umbes 1349","1316":"1316","1349":"1349","1315":"1315","1303":"1303","1412":"1412","1345":"1345","1334":"1334","Abt 1299":"umbes 1299","1300":"1300","1278":"1278","DEC 1350":"detsember 1350","Tamworth Castle, Warwickshire, England":"Tamworth, Staffordshire, England","Whitacre, Warwickshire, England":"Warwickshire, Inglismaa, United Kingdom","Of,, Surrey, England":"Surrey, Inglismaa, United Kingdom","Tamworth, Warwickshire, England":"Warwickshire, Inglismaa, United Kingdom","England":"Inglismaa, United Kingdom","Warwickshire, England":"Warwickshire, Inglisma